title: Russian Natural Gas Stoppage, Europe and Asia, 1.7.2009
name: Russian Natural Gas Stoppage, Europe and Asia, 1.7.2009
description:
This dataset displays important figures about the exportation and consumption of Russian natural gas to several European and Asian countries in 2006, 2007, and the first week of the new year 2009. Recent tensions between Ukraine and Russia are to blame for the halt in these supplies. 

The data includes: Russian Gas Supply in billions of cubic feet 2006, Russian Gas Supply in billions of cubic feet 2007, Russian Gas as a % of 2006 consumption, Gas supply halts, Gas supply halts value

The data comes from an article published in the WSJ. They obtained their data from the following sources: EIA International Energy Annual, 2007 (domestic consumption figures) Gazexport as cited by Energy Intelligence; march 2008 (Exports 2006 and 2007), Gazprom company reports (Sales to Baltic and CIS States), Reuters, Associated Press, Dow Jones Newswires and WSJ Research (Status of Russian gas supplies by country as of 3pm EST on 1.7.2009)

From the data I decided to create a value for the drop in supply from Russia to each country called 'Gas Supply Stoppage'. It gives a percentage of the drop in gas supply from Russia. I then matched the percentage drop to create a value that is represented as the Gas Supply Stoppage value. This was done to easily map the figures. Some countries had stoppage figures that were not percentages but phrases. They include significant reductions, complete halt, and unknown. I assigned these phrases the following values: significant reductions = 60, complete halt = 100, and unknown is 0.

For more information view the article that is listed as a citation url.
